[2] US (Colorado): cost of infection
Date: Sat 25 Nov 2017, 6:32 AM
Source: Forbes [edited]
https://www.forbes.com/sites/tarahaelle/2017/11/25/just-two-measles-cases-cost-taxpayers-68192-in-colorado/#1b91858c7107


Even when infectious diseases don't cause long-term serious harm, they cost money. When that disease is a serious, extremely contagious vaccine-preventable disease like measles, the costs run into tens of thousands of dollars - which come straight from taxpayers' pockets.

Most diseases that can be prevented by vaccines are "notifiable diseases," which means health care providers and local officials are legally required to report cases so that the government can track and respond to outbreaks and prevent further infections.

So aside from the cost of health care and lost productivity from missing work and school, notifiable diseases cost money for local, state and sometimes national officials to interview those infected, identify all others exposed to the disease, and take measures to prevent the disease from spreading.

In the case of 2 unrelated measles cases in Denver, Colorado between July 2016 and January 2017, the public funds needed for response, surveillance and disease control totaled USD 68 192. The cost included personnel and supply costs in Colorado's Tri-County Health Department for Adams, Arapahoe, and Douglas counties.

"Each case resulted in multiple exposures at health care facilities and public venues, and activated an immediate and complex response by local and state public health agencies," wrote Grace E. Marx, MD, from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Epidemic Intelligence Service, and her coauthors.

In both cases, the people with measles had traveled to countries where measles is still regularly circulating. Measles is no longer endemic, or regularly circulating on its own, in the US and in all of the Americas. But cases can still be imported and lead to serious outbreaks, such as at Disneyland several years ago and in Minnesota last year [2016]. Most people who get sick during these outbreaks are unvaccinated.

The 1st case was a 14-month-old boy who contracted measles during a 3-month visit to India. He was unvaccinated even though the CDC recommends infants old get the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine before overseas travel if they're at least 6 months old. During the time he was infectious, from 8--16 July 2016, a total of 283 people were exposed to his infection at 8 locations, including 3 health care facilities, an apartment building and a children's math and reading center.

Although 83 percent of those people were fully vaccinated, nearly all those who weren't had to receive treatment to prevent infection (post-exposure prophylaxis). No additional cases occurred, though one 8-month-old infant who required vaccination developed a rash and fever from the vaccine. The total cost of the public health response was USD 49 769.

The 2nd case was a 33-year-old man in Denver who contracted measles in Thailand during travel from 20 Nov--14 Dec 2016. While infectious, he visited 17 businesses and 2 health care facilities, exposing 232 people. Again, no additional infections occurred, but the public health response totaled USD 18 423. The cost was lower because reporting to public health authorities was delayed, which made post-exposure prophylaxis no longer an effective option.

"Even a single case of measles can cause substantial economic and personnel burden to public health systems," wrote the authors. "This burden can be decreased by improving measles-mumps-rubella vaccination rates, increasing timely reporting of suspected or confirmed measles cases, and optimizing coordinated public health response."

The authors cited previous measles infections whose public health responses cost from USD 5655 -- USD 181 679 for personnel, tracing all exposed persons and administering postexposure prophylaxis.

"In addition to the direct costs from personnel hours, these investigations place considerable burden on public health agencies," the authors wrote. "Reprioritization of public health programming during these urgent investigations has the potential to cause delay in delivering other necessary public health services."

[Byline: Tara Haelle]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The cost of treating infectious disease cases and preventing further spread can be astronomical. On the other hand, "Vaccination is one of the most cost-effective and successful public health interventions. Each year, vaccines save an estimated 6 to 9 million lives worldwide, including the lives of 3 million children. In the United States, vaccinations have decreased most vaccine-preventable childhood diseases by more than 95 percent. Vaccines have minimized or eliminated outbreaks of certain diseases that were once lethal to large numbers of people, including measles and polio in the United States and smallpox worldwide. But because the bacteria and viruses that cause diseases still exist, the public health gains achieved through vaccines can only be maintained by ensuring that vaccination rates remain high enough to prevent outbreaks. When vaccinated people in a given population increase, the likelihood that a susceptible person will come into contact with an infected person decreases; it ultimately becomes difficult for a disease to maintain a chain of infection. Although the vaccination rate required to achieve herd immunity varies by vaccine, it typically ranges from 80 percent to 95 percent of a given population.

"Herd immunity is critical for protecting the health of many groups of people who are especially vulnerable to communicable diseases: those who cannot be vaccinated, either because they are too young or because an immunological condition makes vaccination too risky; those who choose--or whose parents choose for them--not to get vaccinated for nonmedical reasons such as religious or personal beliefs; and those who have been vaccinated but whose immunological response is insufficient to protect them from potential infection." [excerpted from http://ampr.gs/2iZlnSA]

[A Healthmap/ProMED of the United States can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5472558,106 and Colorado, United States at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5472558,209.]

