[4] Europe (UK, Birmingham, Midlands)
Date: Tue 28 Nov 2017, 1:57 PM
Source: Birmingham Mail [edited]
http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/nine-children-birmingham-measles-outbreak-13965336


Health chiefs have issued an urgent warning as they confirmed 9 children have contracted measles in the city [Birmingham]. Parents are being urged to ensure their family has had vaccinations in the wake of the outbreak of the highly infectious illness.

The disease can lead to serious chest infections, ear infections, brain swelling and, in some cases, brain damage. Younger children are particularly vulnerable but anyone with weakened immune systems - such as cancer patients - are also at risk.

People are being urged to stay at home and contact their GP or NHS 111 for advice if they suspect they could be suffering from measles.

"Measles is a highly infectious viral illness. If you think you could have measles, it is really important to stay away from areas where you could come into contact with lots of other people - especially vulnerable patients in hospitals, care homes or other settings."

Measles has been eliminated in UK, say global health leaders "It is possible for anyone at any age to get measles and the illness can be more severe in teenagers and adults than in young children."

Public Health England (PHE) has reported an increase in measles across the country over the year [2017].

Dr Sibal added: "The free MMR vaccine is a safe and effective way of protecting against measles, as well as mumps and rubella. It's particularly important for parents to take up the offer of MMR vaccination for their children when offered at 1 year of age and as a pre-school booster at 3 years, 4 months of age. If children and young adults have missed these vaccinations in the past, it's important to take up the vaccine now from GPs, particularly in light of the recent cases in Birmingham."

Last year [2016] outbreaks were reported in the South West of England and London, while earlier this month [November 2017] outbreaks were reported in Dublin and Meath in Ireland.

All of the cases are in children and young adults who haven't received the MMR vaccine with health officials advising anyone who missed the jab to visit their GP.

The warning comes despite global health chiefs declaring measles had been 'eliminated' in the UK in September this year [2017].

Dr Mary Ramsay, head of immunisation at Public Health England, said in September [2017]: "We are delighted that the World Health Organisation has confirmed that the UK achieved measles elimination in 2016 and that rubella elimination continues to be sustained."

Measles symptoms to be aware of include: high fever; sore, red, watery eye; coughing; aching and feeling generally unwell; a blotchy red brown rash, which usually appears after the initial symptoms.

[Byline: Cathrina Hulse]

